    image: imgFungalInfections,
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Fungal Sepsis", content: "Fungal sepsis, most commonly caused by Candida species (candidemia), occurs when fungi enter the bloodstream, typically in immunocompromised, critically ill patients with risk factors including broad-spectrum antibiotic use, central venous catheters, total parenteral nutrition, abdominal surgery, and neutropenia. Candida albicans forms biofilm on indwelling catheters, providing a protected reservoir for continuous seeding into the bloodstream. The innate immune response to fungal cell wall components (beta-glucan, mannan) involves pattern recognition by dectin-1 and mannose receptors on macrophages and neutrophils, but the inflammatory response is often less robust than in bacterial sepsis, leading to delayed diagnosis. Serum beta-D-glucan and blood cultures (which have only 50% sensitivity for candidemia) guide diagnosis. The nurse monitors for signs of disseminated candidiasis (new skin lesions, endophthalmitis, hepatosplenic candidiasis), administers prescribed antifungal therapy (echinocandins as first-line, fluconazole for susceptible species), ensures removal of central venous catheters (source control), monitors hepatic and renal function during antifungal therapy, and obtains repeat blood cultures to document clearance." },
    riskFactors: ["Prolonged broad-spectrum antibiotic therapy (disrupts normal flora, promotes Candida overgrowth — risk increases with each additional antibiotic)","Central venous catheters (Candida biofilm formation on catheter surfaces provides continuous bloodstream seeding)","Total parenteral nutrition (TPN provides glucose-rich medium promoting fungal growth; lipid emulsions also support Candida)","Neutropenia (ANC <500 cells/μL) or immunosuppressive therapy (chemotherapy, transplant immunosuppression, high-dose corticosteroids)","Recent abdominal surgery or GI perforation (translocation of Candida from colonized GI tract into bloodstream)","ICU stay >7 days with multiple invasive devices (endotracheal tube, urinary catheter, arterial lines)","Candida colonization at multiple body sites (predictive of invasive candidiasis — colonization index used in some ICUs)"],
    diagnostics: ["Blood cultures using fungal isolator tubes: gold standard but only 50% sensitive for candidemia; draw from peripheral vein AND through central line; species identification critical for antifungal selection","Serum beta-D-glucan (BDG): pan-fungal biomarker; sensitivity 75-80% for invasive candidiasis; serial monitoring recommended; false positives with certain IV immunoglobulins, gauze packing, and hemodialysis membranes","CBC with differential: leukocytosis or leukopenia; persistent unexplained neutropenia despite growth factor support may suggest fungal etiology","Comprehensive metabolic panel: monitor renal function (creatinine) and hepatic function (AST, ALT, bilirubin) as baseline and during antifungal therapy","Dilated ophthalmologic examination: screen for Candida endophthalmitis (occurs in 2-16% of candidemia — can cause permanent vision loss if untreated)","CT abdomen for hepatosplenic candidiasis: 'bull's-eye' lesions in liver and spleen on imaging in patients with prolonged neutropenic fever"],
    management: ["Echinocandin therapy as first-line: micafungin 100 mg IV daily or caspofungin 70 mg loading then 50 mg daily or anidulafungin 200 mg loading then 100 mg daily","Central venous catheter removal: source control is ESSENTIAL — remove all central lines if possible within 24-48 hours of positive cultures; associated with improved survival","Repeat blood cultures every 24-48 hours until negative: treatment duration is minimum 14 days after FIRST negative blood culture","Fluconazole step-down: transition from echinocandin to fluconazole 400 mg daily once Candida species confirmed susceptible and patient clinically improving","Ophthalmology consultation within 1 week of positive blood culture for dilated fundoscopic exam to rule out endophthalmitis","Echocardiogram: obtain in patients with prolonged candidemia or prosthetic valves to evaluate for Candida endocarditis"],
